						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Fact of the matter is, we already know exactly how the digital portion works, and the outside-the-IC part is so simple there's nothing variable there.</div><br />Is this known for both the NES and Super NES?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The <strong>only possible</strong> remaining variation in colors would be if the output impedance from the NES varies significantly across the 10 different voltages the PPU can emit. And even then, that should really just come down to a little variation in net hue rotation, net brightness, or net saturation.</div><br />Slew rate effects may produce a saturation-dependent hue rotation, where the more saturated colors ($1x and $2x) are rotated more than the ones with weaker chroma ($0x and $3x).</div>

