						<div class="postbody">This is what the palette looks like, in case you want to use it in a paint program:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=4481" alt="fbx-palette.png" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">fbx-palette.png [ 2.93 KiB | Viewed 3922 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br />Its colors are less muted than <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=159309#p159309" class="postlink">the palette that I had been using</a>.<br /><br />The Python program that produced this image:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">#!/usr/bin/env python<br />&quot;&quot;&quot;<br />indexed image palette replacer<br />made by Damian Yerrick, licensed under CC Zero<br />&quot;&quot;&quot;<br />from PIL import Image<br /><br />with open(&quot;FBX-Accuracy.pal&quot;, &quot;rb&quot;) as infp:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; palette = infp.read()<br />palette = palette&#91;:192&#93;*4<br /><br /># this png file is written by savtool available at<br /># https://pineight.com/nes/#editor<br />im = Image.open(&quot;savtool-swatches.png&quot;)<br />im.putpalette(palette)<br />im.save(&quot;fbx-palette.png&quot;)<br /></div></div>

